Stockholm To July. The s Inſtant, the two Ambaſſadors of
Poland made their encry in this city, they were received
by ſome Senators; the Citizens being in their Armes, and
all the Forces that were here in Bait alia in the place where
their Lodgings were prepared, and where they were that
day ſumptuouilly entertained. The next day, two Senators
went to viſit them from his Sweadiſh Majeſty, to declare un-
to them that they were very welcome, and that his faid Ma-
jelly wiſhed they had come fooner, to prevent the breach, &
the Ceffation of Armes between the two Crowns, where
unto he had been neceffitated for the reaſons hce would .c-
qurint them with; yet affuring them, that though his Armies
had already begun to march, yet hee was no lefle inclined to
Peace. The 7th, his ſaid Majeſty gave them a publique Ad-
dience, to whom they (pake in ſuch a fort, as that both hea
and the Senate were very well ſatisfied, in particular with
his credentialls, in the Seal whereof the Arms of Sweadland
were left our. The Chancellor Oxenft:ern, the Count de la
Gardie, and Mr. Biele Commiflioners appointed for that
Treaty, weot afterwards to the ſaid Ambaſſadors to bear
their Propoſitions. And fince that time hise ſaid Majefty
bath acquainted Mr. D' Avangout the French Ambaffador,

Frances order, that hee will be glad to have a private con-
ference with them, hoping that the bafineſſe wil bee there-
by much forwarded, ſpecially if they would reolve tool-
Tuw him into Pomerania. Whereupon many are in hope of
a fair accommodation. But wee begin here to bee jealous
of che Emperours arming, upon the advice wee had that he
bath fene forces towards the Borders of Sileſia and along the
River of Odor. The Tartarian Ambaffadors is gone back
again, without viſiting thofe of Poland, which makes us
think there will not bee hereafter a great correſpondence be-
cween their Maffers.

This day was execution at Kingſtone in Surrey, for the
'Gaol delivery of that County; where four women were put
to death.
The firſt that was executed was a woman that had three
Husbands, and the left of them was a Sick Throfter, with
whom the bad lived in good faſhion, yet when he was
not well of a cold, and ſent for ſome honey to take for it,
Th got po fon and mixed it with his honey, & fopoyloned
him, for which ſhe was this day burnt to death; And when
Thce came to the Stake, where was a Minifter of the place,
and Mr. Bellers of the Tower of London, a godly man well
known, who called upon her to bee fenfible of her condition,
and ſeek for Peace with God, yet fhe did not much regard

prefted with, only cryed out againſt pride, ſaying that that
